Fortunately, jinja2 filters are just python functions. So all of that is possible. I'd encourage something like (off-the-cuff psuedo-code ahead):

```python
class ProcessResult:
    def __init__(self, result):
        self.result = result

    def __str__(self):
        return self.result.stdout.decode()

def subp(cmd, check=False, **kwargs):
    kwargs['stdout'] = subprocess.PIPE
    kwargs['stderr'] = subprocess.PIPE
    result = subprocess.run(cmd, check=False, **kwargs)
    if result.returncode and check:
        raise yasha.RenderError(result.stderr)
        # or...
        raise click.ClickException('{} returned {}'.format(cmd, result.stderr)
    return ProcessResult(result)
```

I've not tested that code, but it should allow for `stdout` to be printed by default. I.e. `{{ 'git rev-parser --short HEAD' | subp }}` --> abcd123. Of course, supporting filters would have an easier time finding `stdout`, `resultcode`, etc. And, by default, click.ClickException returns 1, which any bash script with `-e` set, would automatically halt at.

