This time I think that I DO find a bug for you :)
It is in `MMDPmxParser.cpp` Line 102, the utf-16 to utf-8 encoder which I have complained about before.

I got the function prototype and write it here:
<pre>template &lt;typename u16bit_iterator, typename octet_iterator&gt;
octet_iterator utf16to8 (u16bit_iterator start, u16bit_iterator end, octet_iterator result)
{
    while (start != end)
    {
        uint32_t cp = utf8::internal::mask16(*start++);
        ...... //omitted
        result = utf8::append(cp, result);
    }
    return result;
}
</pre>
We can easily point out that the function uses `start++` to iterate each utf-16 characters.

But this function is called by `utf8::utf16to8( sourceStart, sourceStart + size, targetStart );`, here the type of `sourceStart` is `const char*`, so the loop will actually runs "size" times, while we know that it should only runs half as many as it. (Each utf-16 character cost 2 bytes)

I fixed it by `utf8::utf16to8( (uint16_t*)sourceStart, (uint16_t*)sourceStart + size / 2, targetStart );`

Also, several lines later, `result.assign(targetReserved, targetStart - targetReserved);`
Here `utf16to8` does not change `targetStart`, so the second parameter is always 0, which makes `result` a blank string. Simply uses `return std::string(targetStart);` can solve the problem. If you do so, you also need to initialize `targetStart`.

