@meejah sorry for confusion! indeed, after relooking, I think we should discuss this more deeply and take the chance to come up with a sustainable solution.

So on the wire, a HELLO message looks like this:

```
[HELLO, Realm|uri, Details|dict]
```

The interesting stuff is in the Details, eg here is a client offering two authmethods:

```
[HELLO, "realm1", {
   "authid": "alice";
   "authrole": "user",
   "authmethods": ["foo", "bar"],
   "authextra": {
      "param1": 23,
      "param2": 666
   }
}]
```

All existing autmethods pack their knobs into `authextra` (which must be a dict - if present) - eg WAMP-cryptosign is looking for a `pubkey` attribute in `authextra`.

Following that approach, WAMP-SCRAM knobs that a client wants to announce to a router should also go as attributes into `authextra` dict in the `details` dict of the HELLO message.

---

Now, looking at the structure of the `details` in above example, it seems actually weird that there is an option to have a _list_ of `authmethods`, but only _one_ `authextra` for all these.

What if I wanted to announce that I am (as a client) willing to authenticate under 2 specific parameter sets of WAMP-SCRAM - and none else?

This isn't possible in the current message structure, as the knobs are shared for the full list of authmethods.

What we could do is allow `authmethods` to take a more complex structure, eg

```
[HELLO, "realm1", {
   "authmethods": [
      {
         "authmethod": "foo",
         "authid": "alice",
         "authrole": "user",
         "authextra": {
            "param1": 23,
            "param2": 666
         }
      },
      {
         "authmethod": "bar",
         "authid": "bob",
         "authrole": "guest",
         "authextra": {
            "param1": 42,
            "param3": "foo"
         }
      }
   ]
}]
```

The semantics could be: if there is a knob at the authmethod level, take that, if not take the knob at the (global) authextra, if none, take default.

