@voith I believe what's going on here is the following (@carver can verify)

The `sign` functionality between web3js, web3py, geth, parity, etc has not been implemented consistently or to any specific standard.  The *most* standardized one (what web3.py does and what geth uses) is fundamentally broken for certain inputs.

So, I think we're either removing `sign` or moving it to different name in preparation for in incoming message signing standard that isn't yet finalized.

