@iamhasibrahman, the canonical way to store SK/AK pairs is indeed config files or environment variables. It's good practice to limit the IAM user's permissions to the minimum required to do the job.

If you're really uncomfortable with storage of SK/AK pairs on a local device, you could use a small instance (t2.nano should be plenty) with an IAM Role assigned to it. When you do that, `credstash` will seek credentials from the instance metadata service. AWS will do automatic credential rotation and you will not have to manage them at all.

More on IAM Roles: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/iam-roles-for-amazon-ec2.html

